photos.Locality: stakeout Dusky Warbler, South San Francisco (2016)
photos.Observation Details: Refound it after an absence of 1 hour+.   Alone.  Dull-brown 'dusky' back and crown, light unstreaked chin and breast, some faint warm ochre tones on underbelly.  Defined white supercilium and under-eye subloral with a smudgy black eye line extending far back. The supercilium  becoming buff behind the lores.   Short thin bill.  Legs are orange-red.   Would forage low in the thicker bushes, preferring shade and then fly 50-100 yards at a time.  Always seemed to 'tink' a few times before taking flight, and sometimes while in the air.

Continuing.   Seen on arrival with 12 other birders at the base of a coyote bush in the field.   Small warbler, about the size and shape of a Common Yellowthroat, except that it has a long tail.   "Dusky" brown back, grayish breast with no clear demarcations and some faintly yellow tones especially around flanks , no wingbar.  Head was same color as back, and I saw the white supercilium briefly.  Never in full view nor in full sunlight until it flew (at about 20' height) into alders - where I was really able to pick up some yellow tones on the flanks.  Refound about 150 yds up creek in very simillar bush at 9:45AM.   Photos taken.

photos.Observation Details: I thought this was a Lesser Whitethroat when I was taking the photo - now realize it isn't.   Bird was slightly larger and very shy, basically immobilized inside the tree.   Believe it to be an immature Western Orphean Warbler (though possibly Barred(?)) - due to dark thick bill, ear coverts are darker gray than the rest of face, lighter lores.  Online photos of juvenile birds show that both species can have dark eye. Comments welcome.
